Plain — Semantics
Nerijus Ramanauskas <nerijus@signaintermedia.com>


EVALUATION MODEL

    Plain evaluates a list of statements left to right. Each statement
    is a node: a keyword followed by zero or more arguments. The walker
    resolves arguments (substituting variables and evaluating nested
    expressions) before looking up the keyword in the frame and invoking
    the bound callable.

    Blocks ({ }) are intentionally deferred — the walker leaves them
    unevaluated so procedures like if and repeat can decide if/when/how
    many times to run them.


STATEMENT vs EXPRESSION

    A statement is a top-level node (no parent). Its return value is
    usually discarded.

    An expression is a node wrapped in [...]. The walker evaluates it
    recursively and substitutes its result as an argument value.

        print [add 1, 2]    ` [add 1, 2] is an expression here


VARIABLES AND FRAMES

    Variables are name-to-value bindings stored in a frame. Frames are
    linked in a chain (lexical scoping): a lookup walks from the innermost
    frame outward until the name is found.

    Assignment is done with = in statement context (no enclosing [...]):

        x = 42
        name = "Plain"

    The = operator cannot be overridden — it is always assignment in
    statement context. Inside [...] it means equality comparison.


CALLABLES

    A callable is a stored function or procedure that can be invoked by
    name, stored in a variable, and passed as an argument.

    Two kinds:

        function   — immutable binding; cannot be reassigned after definition.
        procedure  — mutable binding; can be reassigned at any time.

    Named definition form:

        function  name {parameters} {body}
        procedure name {parameters} {body}

    The name can be a keyword, a quoted string, or an operator symbol:

        function  square {n} { return [n * n] }
        procedure 'greet' {name} { print "Hi, {name}" }
        procedure + {a, b} { return [multiply a b] }   ` operator override

    Anonymous (expression) form — returns a callable value:

        double = [function  {n} { return [n * 2] }]
        greet  = [procedure {n} { print "Hi, {n}" }]

    The named form does not work when the name is already bound as a
    non-operator variable (the walker resolves the keyword before the
    procedure or function sees it). For rebinding a non-operator name,
    use the expression form:

        double = [function {n} { return [n * 2] }]

    Operator symbol names (+, -, *, etc.) are exempt from this: they are
    never resolved by the walker, so the named form always works for them.


STRING INTERPOLATION

    Quoted strings containing unescaped braces are automatically
    expanded at parse time. The tokenizer synthesizes a join expression
    from the literal parts and interpolated values:

        "Score: {score}"         ` equivalent to [join "Score: " score]
        "{a} + {b} = {[a + b]}"  ` equivalent to [join a " + " b " = " [a + b]]

    {name} inserts the value of a variable. {[expression]} inserts
    the result of an arbitrary expression. Both forms convert values
    to strings automatically (same coercion rules as join).

    Strings without braces are treated as plain strings with no extra
    cost. Use \{ and \} to produce literal brace characters:

        "use \{name\} for interpolation"    ` literal braces, no expansion


BUILT-IN PROCEDURES

    Built-in procedures (if, repeat, add, etc.) are registered as mutable
    callables in the root frame at startup. Because they are regular
    bindings they can be overridden, stored, passed as arguments, and
    invoked exactly like user-defined callables:

        op = add;
        print [op 3, 4]    ` 7

        add = [procedure {a, b} { return [a + b + 1] }]

    if — condition chains

        if condition {then}
        if condition {then} else {else}
        if condition {then} else condition {then} else condition {then} else {else}

    "else" followed by a block is the final fallback. "else" followed by
    any non-block value is an elseif condition; the chain continues.

    when — value dispatch

        when target
            value1 {body1}
            value2 {body2}
            else   {default}

    Compares the target against each value using equality. Executes the
    body of the first match and stops. "else" provides a fallback when no
    case matches. Works with strings, integers, reals, and booleans.

    repeat — loop forms

        repeat {body}                              infinite loop (use break to exit)
        repeat count {body}                        counted loop (runs count times)
        repeat {condition} {body}                  conditional loop (while condition is true)
        repeat {variable} times count {body}       counted loop with automatic variable binding

    The last form creates a scoped variable that counts from 0 to count-1:

        repeat {i} times 5 { print i }             prints 0, 1, 2, 3, 4

    The variable lives in a child frame and does not leak into the outer
    scope. The modifier keyword "times" is extensible — future modifiers
    can follow the same natural-language pattern.


INFIX OPERATORS

    The thirteen operator symbols have a special infix calling convention
    when used as the sole argument between a variable name and a value:

        [name op value]

    This is syntactic sugar — it is equivalent to invoking the operator as
    a prefix procedure call with (name_value, value) as arguments:

        [x + 3]    ` same as [+ x 3] once + is bound

    Operator symbols are resolved from the frame at dispatch time, so
    overriding them covers both infix and prefix call sites simultaneously:

        procedure + {a, b} { return [multiply a b] };
        x = 10;
        print [x + 3]    ` 30  (infix, uses override)
        print [+ x 3]    ` 30  (prefix, uses same override)

    The = operator in infix position inside [...] means equality, not
    assignment. The assignment behaviour of = in statement context is
    hardcoded and cannot be overridden.

    Infix is strictly binary. Compound expressions require nesting:

        print [and [x > 0] [x < 10]]


CLOSURES

    Every function and procedure captures the frame in which it was
    defined. When invoked, the callable's own frame is created as a
    child of the captured frame, not the caller's frame. This means
    outer variables stay accessible and mutable — enabling counter
    factories, partial application, and all other closure patterns.

    Assignment (x = value) updates an existing variable wherever it
    lives in the frame chain; a new local is created only if the name
    does not already exist.


RETURN, BREAK, CONTINUE

    return [value]   exits the current callable and yields a value.
    break            exits the nearest repeat loop.
    continue         skips to the next iteration of the nearest repeat.

    All three propagate as special signals through the evaluator.


TYPE INTROSPECTION

    type value       returns a string describing the value's type:
                     "boolean", "integer", "real", "string", "keyword",
                     "list", "callable", "object", or "none".

    do {block}       evaluates the block in a fresh child scope and returns
                     its value. Variables created inside do not leak out.
                     `return` inside the block yields the do expression's value.


CLASSES AND OBJECTS

    class defines a constructor. Calling the constructor creates an object
    whose methods and fields live in a frame — the same structure used for
    variable scopes. From Plain code, there is no distinction between
    objects created in Plain (via class) and objects created in C++ (via
    the host bridge). [type obj] returns "object" for both.

    Named form:

        class Dog {name, age} {
            procedure bark {} { print "{name} barks!" };
            function info {} { return "{name}, age: {age}" }
        }

    Anonymous form (returns a constructor callable):

        Cat = [class {name} {
            function meow {} { return name }
        }]

    Constructing an instance:

        dog = [Dog "Rex", 3]

    Method call — same syntax as any other statement/expression:

        dog bark                 ` statement
        result = [dog info]      ` expression

    Field access — use the field name as the first argument:

        print [dog name]         ` "Rex"

    Methods defined with function produce immutable bindings; those
    defined with procedure produce mutable bindings. Constructor
    parameters become regular fields in the instance.

    Implicit self: methods access fields and other methods directly
    through closure scoping — the instance frame is always in the
    method's parent scope chain. Explicit "self" is only needed when
    passing the instance itself as a value:

        class Calc {n} {
            function double {} { return [n * 2] };
            function quad {} { v = [double]; return [v * 2] }
        }

    Classes are registered in the frame like any other callable, so they
    can be overridden, stored, and passed as arguments.


HOST EXTENSION

    The host application can supply a PLAIN_SUBROUTINE handler on
    PLAIN_CONTEXT that is called for any keyword not found in the frame.
    This is how the Inspector implements print without the library
    containing any I/O.
